''' Ken Murray ''' (24 April 1931 – 2 October 2007) was a reforming prison officer in Scotland during the last third of the twentieth century.<ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12451901.Prison_reformer_Ken_Murray_dies/ Herald Scotsman]</ref>

He was educated at Inverness Technical High School. He worked as a [[Coachbuilder]] until his late twenties when he joined the [[Scottish Prison Service]]. His most notable achievement was the creation of the special unit of [[Barlinnie Prison]] which housed some of the most violent prisoners in the system, including [[Jimmy Boyle (artist)|Jimmy Boyle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/sculpture-by-former-glasgow-hardman-jimy-1049051|title=Sculpture by former Glasgow hardman Jimy Boyle on sale on eBay for £25k|last=Ferguson|first=John|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|location=Glasgow|date=28 January 2010|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref> The unit  was based on treating both staff and prisoners as part of a community in which all had a voice in making decisions and setting programmes.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2007/oct/11/guardianobituaries.prisonsandprobation The Guardian]</ref>
